{"id":"1611.10140","submitter":"Aysel Erey","authors":"Jason Brown and Aysel Erey","title":"A note on the real part of complex chromatic roots","comments":"10 pages, 2 figures","journal-ref":"Discrete Mathematics 328 (2014), 96-101","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A {\\em chromatic root} is a root of the chromatic polynomial of a graph.\nWhile the real chromatic roots have been extensively studied and well\nunderstood, little is known about the {\\em real parts} of chromatic roots. It\nis not difficult to see that the largest real chromatic root of a graph with\n$n$ vertices is $n-1$, and indeed, it is known that the largest real chromatic\nroot of a graph is at most the tree-width of the graph. Analogous to these\nfacts, it was conjectured in [8] that the real parts of chromatic roots are\nalso bounded above by both $n-1$ and the tree-width of the graph.\n  In this article we show that for all $k\\geq 2$ there exist infinitely many\ngraphs $G$ with tree-width $k$ such that $G$ has non-real chromatic roots $z$\nwith $\\Re(z)>k$. We also discuss the weaker conjecture and prove it for graphs\n$G$ with $\\chi(G)\\geq n-3$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 30 Nov 2016 13:32:20 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-12-01"}
